\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Conceptual diagram of the dual-threshold signaling mechanism. The consensus field accumulates confidence signals from all agents. When the majority answer's signal exceeds $\Theta _c$ (green region), consensus is reached. When the minority's combined signal exceeds $\Theta _v$ (red region), veto is triggered. Between the thresholds (yellow region) indicates no consensus yet. This mechanism prevents both premature consensus (via veto) and excessive dissent (via consensus threshold).}}{5}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:fig2}{{2}{5}{Conceptual diagram of the dual-threshold signaling mechanism. The consensus field accumulates confidence signals from all agents. When the majority answer's signal exceeds $\Theta _c$ (green region), consensus is reached. When the minority's combined signal exceeds $\Theta _v$ (red region), veto is triggered. Between the thresholds (yellow region) indicates no consensus yet. This mechanism prevents both premature consensus (via veto) and excessive dissent (via consensus threshold)}{figure.2}{}}
